WEBVTT

00:08.800 --> 00:11.011
Three-quarter power building
to full in two.

00:16.265 --> 00:17.476
Full power.

00:20.729 --> 00:23.232
Unlike other Tupperware parties
you may have attended,

00:23.232 --> 00:25.901
I give thorough product descriptions
and I also make my own snacks.

00:28.445 --> 00:31.657
This Tuesday's menu
will be freshly squeezed nectarine juice

00:31.657 --> 00:34.368
along with lemon-lime bars
on a graham-cracker crust.

00:34.368 --> 00:36.203
Excellent. See you then.

02:15.260 --> 02:16.512
What about this one?

02:17.888 --> 02:19.640
"Butylated hydroxytoluene."

02:20.641 --> 02:24.520
A good rule of thumb is not to eat foods
that share ingredients with jet fuel.

02:25.020 --> 02:26.980
I'll add it to my vocab list.

02:30.067 --> 02:31.818
What color were Dad's eyes?

02:31.818 --> 02:34.738
Blue, like yours.
You know how recessive genes work.

02:34.738 --> 02:36.240
What color was his hair?

02:36.865 --> 02:39.368
Brown.
Where are these questions coming from?

02:40.035 --> 02:42.621
Mrs. Mudford is making us
fill out a family tree,

02:42.621 --> 02:44.831
and I know nothing about Dad.

02:44.831 --> 02:47.084
- You know about your dad.
- No, I don't.

02:47.084 --> 02:50.420
Yes, you do. You know
that he was a brilliant scientist,

02:50.420 --> 02:51.713
that he was kind,

02:51.713 --> 02:53.257
a very funny dancer

02:53.924 --> 02:56.301
and my favorite person
in the world until I met you.

02:59.346 --> 03:02.641
Well, what about his parents?
I need to put them on the tree too.

03:03.141 --> 03:05.394
Your grandparents died in a car accident
when he was young,

03:05.394 --> 03:06.812
then he went to live in a boys' home.

03:07.479 --> 03:09.273
What about your parents?

03:09.273 --> 03:12.442
Ezra and Iris.
We moved around a bit. Not that exciting.

03:13.026 --> 03:14.486
So are we all alone?

03:15.863 --> 03:17.656
We are the opposite of alone.

03:17.656 --> 03:19.950
We have each other, we have Six Thirty,

03:19.950 --> 03:23.120
and we have a huge family waiting
at home for us for dinner.

03:23.620 --> 03:26.498
But you are the chef, so you tell me.
What do you need?

03:27.583 --> 03:30.586
I'll get the flour.
You go to the butcher counter.

03:30.586 --> 03:33.297
- Copy.
- But nothing too lean.

03:33.881 --> 03:34.965
Of course.

03:39.636 --> 03:41.555
- I want a gumball!
- Stop it!

03:41.555 --> 03:43.557
- Get back here!
- I wanna go on the horsey!

03:43.557 --> 03:45.642
- Off of the horse!
- Is everything okay?

03:45.642 --> 03:49.938
Yes. I am so sorry for my little terrors.

03:49.938 --> 03:52.900
- It is quite all right. I understand.
- You know, five minutes.

03:52.900 --> 03:55.027
All I want is five minutes of quiet.

03:55.611 --> 03:56.862
Well, if I'm being greedy,

03:56.862 --> 03:59.448
I'd like them to set the table
and occasionally say thank you.

03:59.448 --> 04:01.825
But five minutes, I'd settle for that.

04:06.205 --> 04:09.374
Those boys were being so rowdy. Geez.

04:09.374 --> 04:11.376
Butylated hydroxytoluene.

04:13.212 --> 04:16.673
That man was out of his mind.
Can you imagine me hosting a TV show?

04:17.882 --> 04:20.135
Seriously? Hear TV pays well.

04:21.720 --> 04:23.388
What's the cost of selling your soul?

04:23.388 --> 04:25.307
Depends. How much they paying?

04:25.807 --> 04:27.518
I thought you sold Tupperware.

04:27.518 --> 04:30.395
I sell Tupperware
so I have time for my research.

04:30.938 --> 04:33.565
I wanna be an actor. Like on <i>Gunsmoke.</i>

04:34.191 --> 04:36.610
You wanna be a lawyer like your mother.

04:36.610 --> 04:38.695
Or, if things don't work out,
a doctor like your father.

04:41.114 --> 04:42.241
You need more milk.

04:42.950 --> 04:44.993
You're lucky you have a father.

04:46.370 --> 04:47.913
You have a father too, bunny.

04:47.913 --> 04:49.623
He's looking down on you right now.

04:49.623 --> 04:52.251
I know. I was just being provocative.

04:52.751 --> 04:54.545
Excuse me, Miss Zott,

04:54.545 --> 04:58.131
but what is this unopened letter from
Phillips Laboratory doing on your counter?

04:58.131 --> 05:02.219
The same Phillips that has called you back
for not one, but two follow-up interviews?

05:02.219 --> 05:04.888
I prefer rejection after my meal.

05:04.888 --> 05:08.183
Would you like me to preview it for you?
I have an excellent poker face.

05:08.684 --> 05:09.977
Open it!

05:09.977 --> 05:11.979
- Open it!
- Open it!

05:11.979 --> 05:15.023
- Open it! Open it!
- Okay, fine.

05:15.023 --> 05:16.191
Read away.

05:18.735 --> 05:21.530
"Dear Miss Zott,
thank you for your continued patience

05:21.530 --> 05:23.699
as we narrow our list of candidates.

05:23.699 --> 05:25.450
We are thrilled--

05:26.159 --> 05:29.705
We are thrilled to tell you
that you have reached our final round

05:29.705 --> 05:31.498
and we intend to make a decision shortly.

05:31.498 --> 05:33.709
Please provide us with references
at your earliest convenience

05:33.709 --> 05:35.377
so that we may..." Blah-blah-blah-blah.

05:35.377 --> 05:37.754
Congratulations, Elizabeth!

05:37.754 --> 05:40.465
- References.
- This is great.

05:40.465 --> 05:41.633
What's a reference?

05:41.633 --> 05:44.178
A reference is when someone you
no longer wish to work with

05:44.178 --> 05:45.554
holds the fate of your next job.

05:46.513 --> 05:49.308
Anyway, I am not getting my hopes up.

06:15.667 --> 06:17.169
I'm here to see Dr. Donatti.

06:17.169 --> 06:20.047
I don't have an appointment, but I was
hoping for the element of surprise.

06:20.756 --> 06:22.424
Dr. Donatti no longer works here.

06:23.675 --> 06:25.177
I didn't realize.

06:25.177 --> 06:27.179
Who might I speak with about possibly--

06:27.179 --> 06:28.263
Thank you.

06:30.390 --> 06:31.850
Elizabeth?

06:33.143 --> 06:34.478
Boryweitz.

06:36.396 --> 06:38.065
So what happened to Donatti?

06:38.899 --> 06:40.442
Well, you know how it goes.

06:41.068 --> 06:43.278
The board was ready for some new blood.

06:43.862 --> 06:46.240
New blood is just old blood recirculated.

06:46.740 --> 06:47.783
Fair point.

06:49.743 --> 06:52.704
I can't tell you how many times I've
wanted to reach out these past few years.

06:54.039 --> 06:55.290
You were just pacing yourself?

06:55.290 --> 06:56.875
I'm sorry, Elizabeth.

06:58.752 --> 07:03.173
Yes, well, I am up for
a chemistry position at Phillips.

07:03.173 --> 07:06.844
Coming here and asking for
a recommendation is extremely unpleasant.

07:06.844 --> 07:09.555
So please be truthful and write
something befitting of my value

07:09.555 --> 07:12.850
or, alternatively, say to my face you will
be blocking my career advancements

07:12.850 --> 07:14.059
as Donatti did.

07:14.059 --> 07:15.936
I mean,
I'm sure you've received a glowing review

07:15.936 --> 07:17.813
from your current lab already.

07:18.397 --> 07:19.940
I currently sell Tupperware.

07:23.694 --> 07:25.362
I'm not going
to write you a good recommendation.

07:25.362 --> 07:26.613
I knew this was a mistake.

07:26.613 --> 07:28.866
I'm not going to do it
'cause I'd like you to come back here.

07:29.366 --> 07:31.243
Here? Are you kidding?

07:31.243 --> 07:32.786
You're an excellent chemist.

07:33.704 --> 07:36.623
And whatever you may think of Hastings,

07:36.623 --> 07:39.251
it's still the best facility
in Southern California.

07:39.251 --> 07:42.254
Far better than Phillips.
You'd be foolish not to consider it.

07:43.630 --> 07:45.674
- Chemist?
- Well, junior chemist.

07:46.258 --> 07:47.259
Which department?

07:47.968 --> 07:49.052
DNA.

07:49.052 --> 07:51.346
Between the Remsen
and my esteemed reputation,

07:51.346 --> 07:55.017
our DNA lab has become the authority
on abiogenesis research.

07:55.017 --> 07:57.227
Just dedicated men doing important work.

07:57.936 --> 08:01.398
And we'd publish together.
I'll even give you second author.

08:03.066 --> 08:04.276
Who would be first author?

08:04.276 --> 08:06.236
Well, it would be me.

08:06.236 --> 08:07.738
You?

08:07.738 --> 08:10.115
The man who stole my work
and then lied about it?

08:10.115 --> 08:14.661
I don-- I can't just put you in charge.
Second author, it-- that's not nothing.

08:14.661 --> 08:17.122
Second author is quite meaningful.

08:22.002 --> 08:23.795
So you'll consider the offer?

08:23.795 --> 08:25.255
I already have.

08:28.634 --> 08:33.972
And who do you think this is
in my family tree?

08:33.972 --> 08:35.097
Lena?

08:35.599 --> 08:36.725
The president?

08:36.725 --> 08:39.602
"Could it be the president?" And no.

08:40.979 --> 08:42.022
Amanda.

08:42.523 --> 08:43.899
Could it be Lassie?

08:43.899 --> 08:48.028
This is a family tree, not a doghouse.
We're talking about people.

08:48.028 --> 08:49.655
People are animals.

08:50.197 --> 08:52.324
No, they aren't, Madeline.
People are humans.

08:52.324 --> 08:55.494
But people are mammals,
and mammals are animals.

08:55.494 --> 08:57.704
Madeline, that's enough.

08:58.872 --> 08:59.873
Tommy?

08:59.873 --> 09:01.166
Could I be an animal?

09:03.544 --> 09:05.712
Now, stop it, Tommy. Stop it. Now--

09:05.712 --> 09:08.841
Oh, no. No, all of you, stop it!

09:08.841 --> 09:11.677
Sit down! Now!

09:12.594 --> 09:13.804
Tommy.

09:15.305 --> 09:18.058
Madeline, see me after class.

09:21.645 --> 09:25.691
- Champagne?
- Yes. Thank you.

09:27.317 --> 09:28.318
Are you joining us?

09:28.318 --> 09:30.362
Oh, no. I don't drink before lunch.

09:31.363 --> 09:32.364
Excuse me.

09:37.911 --> 09:39.079
Zott residence.

09:39.746 --> 09:40.914
Oh, for Christ's sake.

09:42.791 --> 09:47.254
She completely undermined the assignment
and said people are animals.

09:47.921 --> 09:49.464
But people are animals.

09:50.340 --> 09:52.384
Well, that's not the point, is it?

09:52.384 --> 09:55.512
Yesterday, during circle time,

09:55.512 --> 09:58.599
we were having a discussion
about Ralph's pet turtle

09:58.599 --> 10:03.770
and Madeline interrupted and said that
she was unable to find any Norman Mailer

10:03.770 --> 10:05.314
on our bookshelves.

10:05.314 --> 10:07.649
Well, she is interested
in misanthropic characters.

10:08.233 --> 10:09.318
Not surprising.

10:09.318 --> 10:12.154
Are you suggesting
that Madeline is a misanthrope?

10:12.154 --> 10:15.574
I am suggesting
that she is disruptive because--

10:16.200 --> 10:18.785
because she is not challenged here.

10:19.369 --> 10:21.288
I am suggesting
that she would be better off

10:21.288 --> 10:24.082
at a school with
a more advanced curriculum

10:24.082 --> 10:25.626
to keep her engaged.

10:25.626 --> 10:27.628
Some place like the Caswell School.

10:29.004 --> 10:30.380
I've never considered private school.

10:32.216 --> 10:35.636
Well, I think it's time you should.

10:39.389 --> 10:40.474
Thank you for your time.

10:47.606 --> 10:49.566
You do like school, don't you?

10:49.566 --> 10:51.568
Of course I don't like school.

10:52.486 --> 10:54.571
What do you mean? Why didn't you tell me?

10:54.571 --> 10:57.199
Nobody likes school. That's a fact.

10:57.199 --> 10:58.659
That is not necessarily a fact,

10:58.659 --> 11:00.536
and these are things
that you should tell me.

11:00.536 --> 11:02.371
You have enough to worry about.

11:04.790 --> 11:06.083
Amanda!

11:07.876 --> 11:09.461
Mom, can Amanda come over today?

11:09.461 --> 11:12.756
Her dad has to work late, and
we have to practice our secret language.

11:12.756 --> 11:14.132
Of course.

11:14.132 --> 11:19.346
Ank-thay yi-di-goo iss-may zi-di-got.

11:20.722 --> 11:21.723
Come on, you two.

11:30.732 --> 11:33.402
I'm not here to pitch you again.
I'm just here to pick up Amanda.

11:33.402 --> 11:34.736
And I wanted to say,

11:34.736 --> 11:36.989
the chicken pot pie
tasted even better the next day.

11:36.989 --> 11:39.408
I don't know how that's even possible.

11:39.408 --> 11:40.617
Not at all surprising.

11:40.617 --> 11:44.371
When the pie cools, the starch goes
through a process called retrogradation

11:44.371 --> 11:46.748
where the molecules restructure
into a crystalline form.

11:46.748 --> 11:48.959
The flavor compounds are trapped
in said structure,

11:48.959 --> 11:50.919
which makes every bite more flavorful.

11:51.962 --> 11:56.091
Yeah,
I definitely tasted the extra molecules.

11:57.676 --> 11:59.052
Quite delicious.

12:00.387 --> 12:01.972
Come in. I'm making dinner.

12:07.644 --> 12:09.730
I've never seen a kitchen like this.

12:09.730 --> 12:12.274
That's because it is my lab
that I also happen to cook in.

12:12.900 --> 12:14.067
The girls are in the back.

12:14.067 --> 12:16.486
They're teaching
our dog their secret language.

12:17.779 --> 12:19.323
How's Amanda been?

12:19.323 --> 12:21.533
Polite. Funny. Engaging.

12:22.034 --> 12:24.161
Although, I should tell you
she did burst into tears

12:24.161 --> 12:25.913
- when I offered her ants on a log.
- Y--

12:27.581 --> 12:29.833
My wife used to make that for her.

12:30.417 --> 12:32.294
I'm so sorry. When did she pass?

12:32.294 --> 12:34.087
Not dead. Divorced.

12:34.087 --> 12:39.760
She's just in Nevada somewhere
on a trip of spiritual enlightenment.

12:43.013 --> 12:44.389
I don't know how you do it.

12:44.389 --> 12:45.557
Do what?

12:45.557 --> 12:47.434
Keep all the balls in the air.

12:47.434 --> 12:49.811
I've been a single dad
for all of three months,

12:49.811 --> 12:53.482
and I feel like an uncoordinated octopus.

12:53.482 --> 12:56.944
Well, the best advice I ever got
is that no one is equipped to do this,

12:56.944 --> 12:58.487
and then you expand.

12:58.487 --> 13:01.323
You think you can't do it,
and then you do it anyway.

13:01.907 --> 13:05.369
I accidentally put a flask of gin
in her lunch pail last week.

13:05.369 --> 13:08.121
Well, whatever gets her
through Mrs. Mudford's class.

13:10.958 --> 13:12.960
Okay, here we go.

13:13.752 --> 13:16.421
You know,
this is why I thought you'd be a TV star.

13:17.130 --> 13:18.173
And why is that?

13:18.173 --> 13:19.925
Because you respect your audience.

13:20.467 --> 13:22.010
You don't talk down to people.

13:22.010 --> 13:26.348
You meet them where they are,
and you somehow raise them up.

13:26.348 --> 13:29.810
Well, if I were to consider it,
we'd have to be 50-50 partners.

13:29.810 --> 13:31.144
That's not how it works.

13:31.144 --> 13:33.230
Well, then it would never work,
because I won't be--

13:33.230 --> 13:34.481
No, this would be your show.

13:34.481 --> 13:37.401
You would be in charge
of virtually every aspect of it.

13:37.401 --> 13:41.405
If I do my job right,
no one will even know who I am.

13:50.706 --> 13:54.626
I am sending Mad to private school.
It's expensive.

13:55.419 --> 13:58.088
- How much would the job pay?
- More than you've ever made.

14:02.593 --> 14:06.638
My name is Walter,
and I'll be your tour guide for the day.

14:07.389 --> 14:10.142
Let's see. On your right, hair and makeup.

14:10.142 --> 14:12.477
- I can do that myself.
- No, you cannot.

14:12.477 --> 14:17.274
This is Amos, the best boy.
He is a good man.

14:17.274 --> 14:18.859
And what makes him the best?

14:18.859 --> 14:20.402
It's a job title.

14:20.402 --> 14:22.863
- And this is Matt and Robert.
- Hi.

14:22.863 --> 14:24.239
- Hello.
- Props.

14:24.239 --> 14:25.324
What kind of props?

14:25.324 --> 14:27.367
Whisks, spoons, miniature ponies,
whatever you need.

14:28.160 --> 14:32.664
And these ladies
already your biggest fans.

14:32.664 --> 14:36.376
- Shari, Nancy, Lynn and Ronni.
- Hello.

14:36.376 --> 14:38.128
So nice to meet you all.

14:38.128 --> 14:41.173
- Nice to meet you too.
- Okay. Now...

14:42.549 --> 14:44.843
- Coffee?
- Sure, how do you take it?

14:45.552 --> 14:48.180
No, sorry, I get you coffee.
That's my job.

14:49.056 --> 14:50.057
How do you take it?

14:50.849 --> 14:52.434
I'm all set. Thank you.

14:52.434 --> 14:55.771
All right. And finally...

14:58.065 --> 14:59.441
the control room.

15:00.651 --> 15:01.652
Hello.

15:01.652 --> 15:04.530
Then there's your new home.

15:05.531 --> 15:07.074
Kenny, throw 'em on.

15:19.336 --> 15:20.462
Morning, Mr. Pine.

15:21.630 --> 15:26.260
Well, we put our heads together,
came up with every woman's dream kitchen.

15:53.745 --> 15:56.665
Well? What do you think?

16:00.169 --> 16:01.461
This is revolting.

16:04.381 --> 16:06.008
Okay, let's take a five.

16:06.633 --> 16:09.094
Okay. No, I hear your concerns.

16:09.761 --> 16:13.807
Thing is, TV,
it needs to be inviting and fun.

16:13.807 --> 16:16.560
Cooking is not fun. It is vital work.

16:16.560 --> 16:18.812
Right. Okay, idea.

16:18.812 --> 16:21.857
Let's think of the show
as the world's best dinner party.

16:22.608 --> 16:24.818
- When you and Mr. Zott throw dinners--
- There is no Mr. Zott.

16:24.818 --> 16:27.321
I am unmarried. I was never married.

16:29.698 --> 16:32.576
You know what, can we--
Why don't we pick this up later?

16:36.705 --> 16:41.043
So, your-- Was Mad's father--

16:42.211 --> 16:45.047
- Was he stepping out on his wife?
- Oh, no. We were in love.

16:45.047 --> 16:46.632
We were soulmates.

16:46.632 --> 16:49.134
But he died suddenly
before I knew I was pregnant.

16:53.305 --> 16:54.681
I'm so sorry.

16:54.681 --> 16:58.101
I'm sorry for you as well,
for your divorce.

16:58.101 --> 17:00.312
Oh, no. Don't be. We weren't in love.

17:00.312 --> 17:02.022
I don't even know if she has a soul.

17:02.022 --> 17:03.565
You know what? This is what we do.

17:03.565 --> 17:08.862
Think about this whole TV thing
as like a exciting new experiment.

17:13.325 --> 17:15.117
<i>...let's meet four nice people here.</i>

17:15.117 --> 17:16.537
<i>First of all, our champion...</i>

17:19.957 --> 17:22.084
- Zott residence.
- <i>Hello, Miss Zott.</i>

17:22.084 --> 17:25.295
Just wanted to see if you and Mad wanted
to come over tomorrow for a barbecue.

17:25.295 --> 17:26.922
Mention my new marinade.

17:27.673 --> 17:30.926
Well, Mad will be there,
but I may still be studying.

17:30.926 --> 17:32.553
- <i>Studying?</i>
- TV.

17:33.345 --> 17:34.555
How does one study TV?

17:34.555 --> 17:36.223
Turn on channel 4.

17:38.350 --> 17:39.434
Yep.

17:43.230 --> 17:44.481
You got it?

17:44.481 --> 17:45.566
Got it.

17:46.775 --> 17:47.609
Okay.

17:47.609 --> 17:50.362
<i>Now, watch how often
the host smiles or laughs.</i>

17:50.362 --> 17:52.447
<i>My God, why do they smile so much?</i>

17:52.447 --> 17:54.575
There is nothing smile-worthy
about life insurance,

17:54.575 --> 17:57.327
but regardless, I am notating frequency.

17:57.327 --> 17:59.788
I'm also correlating it
with the ratings in the <i>TV Guide</i>,

17:59.788 --> 18:03.292
focusing specifically on the
coveted 24-to-35-year-old demographic.

18:03.292 --> 18:05.586
Is this genius or crazy? I can't decide.

18:05.586 --> 18:07.796
I only have two more weeks
until the show airs,

18:07.796 --> 18:09.256
so I don't have much time to study.

18:09.882 --> 18:13.802
Well, if you need a study break,
we'll be here grilling.

18:13.802 --> 18:17.139
<i>With my new marinade. Bye, Elizabeth.</i>

18:17.139 --> 18:19.850
- <i>Bye, Charlie.</i>
- I love you. I'll miss you.

18:20.726 --> 18:22.769
<i>I thought Charlie was done
with the graveyard shift.</i>

18:25.522 --> 18:27.065
That's what I thought too.

18:27.774 --> 18:31.528
<i>Use the yellow pages:
the first place to look for anything.</i>

18:31.528 --> 18:34.448
Do I need a catchphrase?
Does every show have a catchphrase?

18:34.448 --> 18:35.532
Don't overthink it.

18:35.532 --> 18:37.159
Never understood what that meant.

18:38.243 --> 18:39.328
Goodbye, Miss Zott.

18:39.328 --> 18:40.787
Goodbye, Mrs. Sloane.

18:40.787 --> 18:43.040
<i>...there goes the dirt.</i>

18:43.040 --> 18:44.917
<i>Yes, sir, the secret words are...</i>

18:44.917 --> 18:46.460
Now, honestly.

18:47.336 --> 18:52.591
"In a word, I had been too cowardly
to do what I knew to be right,

18:52.591 --> 18:57.221
as I had been too cowardly
to avoid doing what I knew to be wrong."

18:57.221 --> 18:58.847
What does that mean?

18:58.847 --> 19:01.725
I think Pip is remembering
the times in his life

19:01.725 --> 19:04.811
when he felt pressured
to do or not do things

19:04.811 --> 19:06.313
because they were expected of him.

19:06.897 --> 19:08.690
And that makes him a coward?

19:10.734 --> 19:12.027
Six Thirty.

19:19.284 --> 19:22.704
Hey, Mad,
do you remember Amanda's dad, Walter?

19:23.413 --> 19:25.541
Do you think that
I am suffering from amnesia?

19:25.541 --> 19:26.959
We just saw him.

19:28.836 --> 19:34.633
What I meant to say is that I'm going to
be working with him at the TV station.

19:35.217 --> 19:38.053
So that means our afternoons
are going to look a little different.

19:38.053 --> 19:39.930
But I like our afternoons.

19:40.514 --> 19:42.140
I love our afternoons.

19:43.016 --> 19:47.354
But I'm going to do
what is expected of me, much like Pip.

19:48.272 --> 19:50.816
I don't get it. You're a scientist.

19:50.816 --> 19:55.946
I will be doing science,
just in a kitchen with TV cameras.

19:56.655 --> 19:59.408
Sort of like a teacher for people
who want to learn how to cook.

20:00.242 --> 20:01.827
Plus, there are financial benefits.

20:02.995 --> 20:05.956
I know it'll be tough,
but you say you don't like school,

20:05.956 --> 20:08.333
and I'm wondering if Caswell--

20:08.333 --> 20:10.460
you know,
that big school down by the park--

20:10.460 --> 20:12.296
if it might be a better fit for you.

20:13.005 --> 20:14.590
Do I have a choice?

20:14.590 --> 20:16.258
I would like you to try it,

20:16.258 --> 20:18.552
and you have full veto power
if you hate it.

20:19.219 --> 20:21.471
It sounds like I'm trying it,
and that's about that.

20:22.181 --> 20:24.558
Full veto power. I promise.

20:27.519 --> 20:28.687
I love you, bunny.

20:28.687 --> 20:30.105
I love you too.

20:45.329 --> 20:48.832
<i>Three, two, one, action!</i>

20:48.832 --> 20:52.836
